passages.text: F2Q26 Review: AI Revenue and Margin ExecutionDiverge; Guided Margin Improvement in 2H Will ShiftFocus to Near- Term Execution

Dell executed on better AI server delivery to customers \((\) 8.2bn of revenue vs. JPM of \(\) 7.2\(bn) as well as booked robust incremental orders\) (\) 5.6 bn) in the quarter to support a strong backlog, which is proving instrumental in the raise to the full- year outlook for revenues by about\) \ \(4bn\) at the mid- point from \(\) 103\(bn to\) \ \(107\) bn. At the same time however, the execution to keep up with customer demand on AI servers was done at the expense of margins with supply chain inefficiencies, including expedite costs, further pressuring ISG margins beyond the already envisioned pressure from competitive AI server deals to win business with concentrated customers, leading to only a muted \(\sim\) \(\) 85\(mn increase in guidance for Operating Income for the full - year. As a result, we expect the F2Q performance and the raise to the full - year outlook to lead investors back to conversations and concerns on returns for AI server companies like Dell and Super Micro pursuing large AI server deals at aggressive margins and increasing risk to execution and margins in trying to deliver to the high and lumpy demand on a quarterly basis from customers. Nonetheless, on the positives, the strength in AI server revenues in the quarter as well as the robust orders are helping Dell raise the outlook for AI Server revenues for FY26 from\) \ \(15bn+\) to \(\) 20bn\$ , which is a large increase on a standalone basis and will drive higher confidence in strong growth despite most buy- side investors already expecting a large increase in the outlook. Additionally, the upsides from AI server revenues are helping offset incremental weakness in the traditional infrastructure demand where expectations for Storage and traditional Server demand have deteriorated (in addition to a modest shortfall in CSG as well) relative to expectations 90- days prior; the \(\) 5bn\(AI revenue upside for the year translating to a\) \ \(4bn\) raise in revenues for the company. More importantly, Dell is confident relative to the non- repeat of the supply chain inefficiencies which hobbled ISG margins in F2Q as well as better mix through Storage seasonality setting the company up to report better margins (average of \(\sim 10\%\) implied in 2H vs. \(7.4\%\) in 1H) and profits in the 2H of the fiscal year ( \(\sim 35\%\) increase H/H) despite balanced revenues between 1H and 2H of the year. Given the margin challenges to F2Q, we believe the margin improvement trajectory outlined by the company for the remainder of the year will be an important watchpoint for investors in the near- term, although the robust revenue raise to the full- year as well as the robust outlook for AI server revenues in FY26 will raise expectations for growth outlook of the company in the medium- term, which will be particularly in focus heading into the Analyst Meeting in October where the company is expected to provide updated medium- term targets. We remain Overweight rated with the company well positioned to leverage AI as well as growth in traditional infrastructure demand, in addition to cost discipline and buybacks, to drive strong earnings growth medium- term; maintain Dec- 26 price target of \(\) 145\$ .
Sources for: Style Exposure - J.P. Morgan Global Markets Strategy; all other tables are company data and J.P. Morgan estimates.

expectations as modestly better revenues are offset by modestly softer margin performance. Revenue rose \(+19\%\) y/y to \(\) 29.8\(bn (vs. JPM\) \ \(29.5\) bn, consensus of\) \ \(29.2\) bn, and guidance of\) \ \(28.5 - \$ 29.5\) bn, based by ISG revenue of \(\) 16.8\(bn (vs. JPM\) \ \(16.2\) bn and consensus of \(\) 15.1\(bn based on CSG revenue of\) \ \(12.5\) bn (vs. JPM \(\) 12.9\(bn and consensus of\) \ \(12.8\) bn). Meanwhile, gross margin tracked to \(18.7\%\) (vs. JPM \(\) 19.3\%\(and consensus of\) 19.6\%), driven by a higher mix of lower margin AI server business, as well as supply related one time costs, which in combination with some opex discipline resulted in operating margins of \(7.7\%\) (vs. JPM \(\) 7.8\%\(and consensus of\) 7.9\%). The softer than expected margins drove EPS to track to\) \ \(2.32\) (vs. JPM \(\) 2.31\(, consensus of\) \ \(2.30\) , and guidance of \(\) 2.15- \(\) 2.35\(). Dell reported robust AI server revenues of\) \ \(8.2\) bn (over \(+160\%\) y/y), which along with orders of \(\) 5.6\(bn\) (+75\% y/y) resulted in modest q/q moderation in backlog (\) \ \(11.7\) bn).

- F3Q26 (Oct-end) Guide: Earnings fell short of consensus expectations driven by softer margins, despite better than expected revenues. Revenue is guided to grow \(\sim 11\%\) y/y to \(\) 26.5-\(\) 27.5\(bn (vs. JPM\) \ \(25.7\) bn and consensus of \(\) 26.5\(bn), with ISG expected to grow in the low-twenties percentages y/y, and CSG expected to grow mid single digits. The company anticipates opex to be down low single digits y/y, along with operating income growth of \(+7\%\) y/y. Meanwhile, EPS is guided to \(\) 2.35-\(\) 2.55\(vs. JPM\) \mathrm{a} \(\) 2.56\(and consensus at\) \ \(2.54\) .

- FY26 (Jan-end) Guide: Robust AI Server demand drove upward revision to revenue guide, while EPS revision was relatively modest given mix shift to lower margin business. Dell revised higher their revenue guide to \(\) 105-\(\) 109\(bn (vs. JPM\) \ \(104.5\) bn, consensus of \(\) 105.2\(bn and prior guide of\) \ \(101 - 105\) bn), with ISG revenue guided to grow in the mid-to-high twenties range (vs. high teens prior), driven by anticipated \(\) 20\(bn AI Server revenues (vs.\) \ \(15bn +\) prior) along with flat y/y growth for Storage; and CSG reiterated to grow in the low to mid single digits. Led by improved profits and profitability in 2H of FY26 for both CSG and ISG, overall operating income is expected to rise \(+10\%\) y/y (vs. \(+9\%\) y/y prior). EPS outlook is raised to be in the range of \(\) 9.30-\(\) 9.80\((vs. JPM\) \mathrm{a} \(\) 9.50\(, consensus of\) \ \(9.43\) , and prior guide of \(\) 9.15-\(\) 9.65\()\) .
Dell Technologies (Overweight; Price Target: \(145.00)

We rate shares of DELL Overweight as we are more positively inclined toward the AI- driven compute investment cycle, which should benefit branded server companies, even as the drivers for the remaining businesses are more mixed being subject to the macro backdrop. We have higher confidence in the sustainability of a stronger growth rate in the ISG group led by a stronger compute investment cycle, which sets up the company for double- digit earnings growth as the company cycles past the macro pressures on PCs as well as general purpose servers. While DELL is unlikely to be perceived as a primary beneficiary of an AI investment cycle, we expect all server companies to benefit in relation to sale of higher- end servers with ASP and (operating) margin upside. We see upside to DELL shares stemming from attributing a higher target valuation multiple to the shares relative to its historical average on account of the leverage to AI investments, while a strong rebound in PCs as well as uplift from adoption of AI PCs can provide further upside to our estimates.

Our December 2026 price target of \(145 is based on a 12x target multiple on our CY27 earnings estimate. We believe the 12x target multiple, a premium to the 8x historical average is justified on account of the stronger outlook relative to other Hardware companies over the medium term.
Source: Company reports and J.P. Morgan estimates.
